---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="An AI Agent That Never Forgets an Overdue Invoice — ~/stubborncoder"
  description="How I built an autonomous AI agent that monitors, assesses, and acts on overdue invoices 24/7 — without ever touching a cloud API."
  activeLink="writing"
>

<section class="post-hero">
  <div class="post-hero-bg"></div>
  <div class="post-hero-overlay"></div>
  <div class="post-hero-content wrap">
    <a href="/#writing" class="post-back reveal">&#8592; Back to writing</a>

    <div class="post-meta-top reveal">
      <span>April 2026</span>
      <span>&middot;</span>
      <span>10 min read</span>
    </div>

    <h1 class="reveal">An AI Agent That<br>Never Forgets an <span class="em">Overdue Invoice</span></h1>

    <p class="post-subtitle reveal">
      How I built an autonomous system that monitors accounts receivable around the clock,
      makes collection decisions on its own, and keeps every action traceable — all running
      on local hardware where sensitive financial data never leaves the network.
    </p>

    <div class="post-tags-row reveal">
      <span class="post-tag post-tag--ember">AI Agents</span>
      <span class="post-tag post-tag--gold">AR Collections</span>
      <span class="post-tag">Finance</span>
      <span class="post-tag">Autonomous</span>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<main class="wrap">
  <article class="article">

    <h2 class="reveal">Why AR collections is the perfect problem</h2>

    <p class="reveal">
      If you've worked in finance, you know the rhythm. Every morning someone opens a spreadsheet,
      sorts by days overdue, decides who to chase, drafts an email, maybe makes a call, logs the
      action, moves on. Tomorrow they do it again. And the day after that.
    </p>

    <p class="reveal">
      It's important work — overdue receivables directly impact cash flow — but it follows a pattern
      that's almost mechanical. Scan the accounts. Assess the risk. Take an action based on policy.
      Record what you did. Repeat.
    </p>

    <p class="reveal">
      That's exactly the kind of work where an autonomous agent can thrive. Not replacing the finance
      team's judgment, but handling the <em>repetitive monitoring and initial response</em> so they
      can focus on the exceptions that actually need human attention.
    </p>

    <p class="reveal">
      So I built one.
    </p>

    <h2 class="reveal">The agent loop: cycles, not conversations</h2>

    <p class="reveal">
      Most AI tools are reactive — you ask a question, you get an answer. The Collections Agent is
      different. It runs in <strong>continuous timed cycles</strong>, like a heartbeat. Every cycle
      it wakes up, scans all accounts, assesses what changed, decides what to do, acts, then goes
      back to sleep until the next cycle.
    </p>

    <blockquote class="reveal">
      <p>Scan → Detect changes → Assess each customer → Execute actions → Summarize → Wait → Repeat.</p>
    </blockquote>

    <p class="reveal">
      This matters because collections isn't a one-time event. An invoice that was 5 days overdue
      yesterday is 6 days overdue today. A customer who was low risk last week might have crossed
      a threshold. The agent catches these shifts automatically because it never stops watching.
    </p>

    <p class="reveal">
      Between cycles, the agent compares the current state of each account against the last time
      it looked. If nothing changed for a customer — same invoices, same amounts, no payments —
      it skips re-analysis and moves on. No wasted compute. But the moment a new invoice appears,
      a payment comes in, or an amount crosses a threshold, the agent picks it up immediately.
    </p>

    <h2 class="reveal">Decisions, not just data</h2>

    <p class="reveal">
      Here's where it gets interesting. The agent doesn't just flag overdue invoices — it
      <em>makes collection decisions</em> using structured reasoning.
    </p>

    <p class="reveal">
      For each customer, the AI evaluates the full picture: how many days overdue, the total
      amount at risk, the number of open invoices, the history of prior actions, and whether
      any recent payments have been detected. Based on this, it assigns a risk level —
      Critical, High, Medium, or Low — and decides what action to take.
    </p>

    <p class="reveal">
      The default policy is straightforward:
    </p>

    <div class="policy-grid reveal">
      <div class="policy-row">
        <span class="policy-days">1–15 days</span>
        <span class="policy-action">Monitor</span>
        <span class="policy-desc">Track the account, no outreach yet</span>
      </div>
      <div class="policy-row">
        <span class="policy-days">15–30 days</span>
        <span class="policy-action policy-action--amber">Send email</span>
        <span class="policy-desc">Professional reminder, friendly tone</span>
      </div>
      <div class="policy-row">
        <span class="policy-days">30–60 days</span>
        <span class="policy-action policy-action--warn">Voice call</span>
        <span class="policy-desc">Escalate to phone outreach with a script</span>
      </div>
      <div class="policy-row">
        <span class="policy-days">60+ days</span>
        <span class="policy-action policy-action--critical">Escalate</span>
        <span class="policy-desc">Flag for human review and management action</span>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p class="reveal">
      But — and this is the key — the agent can <strong>deviate from the default policy</strong>
      when the situation warrants it. A 10-day-old invoice for &euro;200,000 might trigger an
      email even though the policy says "monitor." A longtime customer with a clean payment
      history might get an extra grace period. The AI explains its reasoning every time, so
      the finance team can see exactly <em>why</em> it chose to act differently.
    </p>

    <h2 class="reveal">What the agent actually does</h2>

    <p class="reveal">
      It doesn't just make recommendations. It <em>acts</em>:
    </p>

    <div class="takeaway reveal">
      <div class="takeaway-label">Autonomous actions</div>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Drafts collection emails</strong> — the tone escalates automatically: friendly reminder for early overdue, firm for persistent, urgent for critical accounts</li>
        <li><strong>Generates voice call scripts</strong> — complete with text-to-speech playback, ready for the collections team to review or use directly</li>
        <li><strong>Detects payments</strong> — when a customer pays, the agent de-escalates automatically and stops outreach</li>
        <li><strong>Tracks pipeline stages</strong> — each customer moves through not started → email sent → voice call → escalated, with full history</li>
        <li><strong>Produces executive summaries</strong> — every cycle ends with a natural-language overview of what happened and what changed</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <p class="reveal">
      Every single decision and action is logged with timestamps, reasoning, and the data that
      informed it. This isn't a black box — it's an audit trail that a finance team (or an
      auditor) can follow step by step.
    </p>

    <h2 class="reveal">Privacy by design</h2>

    <p class="reveal">
      Financial data is sensitive. Customer names, invoice amounts, payment histories — this isn't
      the kind of information you want flowing through external API calls to cloud services.
    </p>

    <p class="reveal">
      The Collections Agent runs entirely on local hardware. The AI model runs on-premise,
      inference happens on the same machine as the data, and nothing leaves the network.
      For organizations that handle financial data under strict compliance requirements,
      this isn't a nice-to-have — it's a requirement.
    </p>

    <blockquote class="reveal">
      <p>Sensitive financial data never leaves the network. The entire system runs on local hardware.</p>
    </blockquote>

    <h2 class="reveal">What this means for the CFO office</h2>

    <p class="reveal">
      I built this as an AI engineer, but I think about it as a finance person. Here's what
      matters from that perspective:
    </p>

    <p class="reveal">
      <strong>It runs 24/7.</strong> No one needs to check overdue invoices manually every
      morning. The agent is always watching, always current. If something changes at 2 AM,
      it notices at 2 AM.
    </p>

    <p class="reveal">
      <strong>Every decision is traceable.</strong> In finance, "the AI did it" is not an
      acceptable answer. Every action the agent takes comes with a complete reasoning chain.
      Why this customer? Why this action? Why now? It's all logged.
    </p>

    <p class="reveal">
      <strong>Finance teams can ask questions.</strong> The system includes a Q&A assistant
      where anyone on the team can ask natural-language questions about any account.
      "What's the status of Acme Industries?" "Which customers were escalated last week?"
      "What's the total overdue amount above 30 days?" No reports to build, no pivot tables
      to wrestle with.
    </p>

    <p class="reveal">
      <strong>The pattern is reusable.</strong> The agent loop — scan, assess, act, log,
      repeat — isn't specific to collections. The same architecture applies to cash flow
      forecasting, budget variance monitoring, vendor payment optimization, or audit trail
      analysis. Collections is just the first use case.
    </p>

    <h2 class="reveal">Try it yourself</h2>

    <p class="reveal">
      The agent is running live with a demo dataset. You can watch it cycle through
      accounts, see its reasoning, read the emails it drafts, and explore the full
      dashboard — including the pipeline visualization and Q&A assistant.
    </p>

    <div class="cta-box reveal">
      <a href="https://collections.stubborncoder.cloud/" target="_blank" class="cta-link">
        <span class="cta-dot"></span>
        Open the live demo at collections.stubborncoder.cloud &#8594;
      </a>
    </div>

    <p class="reveal">
      If you work in finance and this resonates — or if you're building agents for enterprise
      use cases — I'd love to hear from you.
    </p>

    <div class="article-footer reveal">
      <div class="article-footer-label">Connect</div>
      <div class="resource-links">
        <a href="https://linkedin.com/in/daviddiaztrapero" target="_blank" class="original-link">LinkedIn &#8594;</a>
        <a href="https://stubborncoder.github.io" class="original-link original-link--gh">Blog &#8594;</a>
      </div>
    </div>

  </article>

  <section class="more-posts">
    <div class="more-posts-title">More writing</div>
    <a href="/blog/multimodal-embeddings" class="more-row">
      <span class="more-date">2026.04</span>
      <span class="more-title">Multimodal Embeddings: One Model, One Vector Space</span>
      <span class="more-src">LinkedIn</span>
    </a>
    <a href="/blog/semantic-caching-hana" class="more-row">
      <span class="more-date">2026.03</span>
      <span class="more-title">Semantic Caching for SAP HANA Cloud</span>
      <span class="more-src">LinkedIn</span>
    </a>
    <a href="/blog/hybrid-retrieval-hana" class="more-row">
      <span class="more-date">2026.03</span>
      <span class="more-title">Hybrid BM25 + Vector Retrieval for SAP HANA Cloud</span>
      <span class="more-src">LinkedIn</span>
    </a>
  </section>
</main>

</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .post-hero { position: relative; padding: 10rem 0 4rem; overflow: hidden; }
  .post-hero-bg { position: absolute; inset: 0; background: url('https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1554224155-6726b3ff858f?w=1920&q=80') center/cover no-repeat; filter: blur(8px) saturate(0.3) brightness(0.25); transform: scale(1.05); transition: filter var(--ease); }
  :global([data-theme="light"]) .post-hero-bg { filter: blur(8px) saturate(0.35) brightness(1.1); }
  .post-hero-overlay { position: absolute; inset: 0; background: var(--hero-overlay); mask-image: linear-gradient(to bottom, rgba(0,0,0,0.3) 0%, rgba(0,0,0,1) 70%); -webkit-mask-image: linear-gradient(to bottom, rgba(0,0,0,0.3) 0%, rgba(0,0,0,1) 70%); }
  .post-hero-content { position: relative; z-index: 2; max-width: 720px; }
  .post-back { font-size: 0.75rem; color: var(--text-lo); display: inline-flex; align-items: center; gap: 6px; margin-bottom: 2rem; transition: color 0.2s; text-decoration: none; }
  .post-back:hover { color: var(--ember); }
  .post-meta-top { display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 1rem; margin-bottom: 1.5rem; font-size: 0.72rem; color: var(--text-lo); flex-wrap: wrap; }
  .source-badge { padding: 2px 8px; border-radius: 3px; border: 1px solid var(--ember-border); color: var(--ember); font-size: 0.65rem; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.04em; }
  .post-hero h1 { font-family: 'Libre Baskerville', serif; font-size: clamp(2rem, 4.5vw, 3rem); font-weight: 400; line-height: 1.25; color: var(--text-hi); letter-spacing: -0.02em; margin-bottom: 1.5rem; }
  .post-hero h1 .em { color: var(--ember); font-style: italic; }
  .post-subtitle { font-size: 1rem; color: var(--text); max-width: 560px; line-height: 1.8; }
  .post-tags-row { display: flex; gap: 0.5rem; flex-wrap: wrap; margin-top: 1.5rem; }
  .post-tag { font-size: 0.65rem; padding: 3px 8px; border-radius: 4px; border: 1px solid var(--border); color: var(--text-lo); }
  .post-tag--ember { color: var(--ember); border-color: var(--ember-border); background: var(--ember-glow); }
  .post-tag--gold { color: var(--gold); border-color: rgba(212,166,69,0.2); background: var(--gold-dim); }

  .article { max-width: 720px; padding: 4rem 0 6rem; }
  .article h2 { font-family: 'Libre Baskerville', serif; font-size: 1.4rem; font-weight: 400; color: var(--text-hi); margin-top: 3rem; margin-bottom: 1rem; padding-top: 2rem; border-top: 1px solid var(--border); }
  .article h2:first-child { border-top: none; padding-top: 0; margin-top: 0; }
  .article p { font-family: 'Libre Baskerville', serif; font-size: 0.95rem; line-height: 1.9; color: var(--text); margin-bottom: 1.25rem; }
  .article strong { color: var(--text-hi); font-weight: 600; }
  .article em { color: var(--ember); font-style: italic; }
  .article blockquote { border-left: 3px solid var(--blockquote-border); background: var(--blockquote-bg); padding: 1.25rem 1.5rem; margin: 2rem 0; border-radius: 0 8px 8px 0; }
  .article blockquote p { font-style: italic; color: var(--text-hi); margin-bottom: 0; font-size: 0.92rem; }

  /* Policy grid */
  .policy-grid { margin: 2rem 0; border: 1px solid var(--border); border-radius: 10px; overflow: hidden; }
  .policy-row { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 100px 120px 1fr; gap: 1.5rem; padding: 1rem 1.5rem; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border); align-items: center; }
  .policy-row:last-child { border-bottom: none; }
  .policy-days { font-size: 0.82rem; color: var(--text-hi); font-weight: 500; }
  .policy-action { font-size: 0.75rem; color: var(--ash); font-weight: 500; }
  .policy-action--amber { color: var(--gold); }
  .policy-action--warn { color: var(--ember); }
  .policy-action--critical { color: #c0503e; font-weight: 600; }
  .policy-desc { font-size: 0.78rem; color: var(--text); }

  .takeaway { background: var(--bg-card); border: 1px solid var(--ember-border); border-radius: 10px; padding: 2rem; margin: 2.5rem 0; }
  .takeaway-label { font-size: 0.68rem; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.1em; color: var(--ember); font-weight: 600; margin-bottom: 1rem; }
  .takeaway ul { list-style: none; padding: 0; }
  .takeaway li { font-family: 'Libre Baskerville', serif; font-size: 0.88rem; color: var(--text); padding: 0.5rem 0; padding-left: 1.2rem; position: relative; line-height: 1.7; }
  .takeaway li::before { content: '›'; position: absolute; left: 0; color: var(--ember); font-weight: 700; }

  /* CTA box */
  .cta-box { margin: 2.5rem 0; }
  .cta-link {
    display: inline-flex; align-items: center; gap: 10px;
    font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--text-hi);
    padding: 1rem 1.5rem; border: 1px solid var(--ember-border);
    border-radius: 10px; transition: all 0.25s; text-decoration: none;
    background: var(--ember-glow);
  }
  .cta-link:hover { background: var(--ember); color: white; border-color: var(--ember); }
  .cta-link:hover .cta-dot { background: white; box-shadow: 0 0 6px white; }
  .cta-dot {
    width: 8px; height: 8px; border-radius: 50%;
    background: var(--ember); flex-shrink: 0;
    animation: cta-pulse 2s infinite;
  }
  @keyframes cta-pulse { 0%, 100% { opacity: 1; box-shadow: 0 0 6px var(--ember); } 50% { opacity: 0.4; box-shadow: none; } }

  .article-footer { border-top: 1px solid var(--border); padding-top: 2.5rem; margin-top: 3rem; }
  .article-footer-label { font-size: 0.68rem; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.1em; color: var(--text-lo); margin-bottom: 1rem; }
  .resource-links { display: flex; gap: 0.75rem; flex-wrap: wrap; }
  .original-link { display: inline-flex; align-items: center; gap: 8px; font-size: 0.82rem; color: var(--text-hi); padding: 0.65rem 1.1rem; border: 1px solid var(--border); border-radius: 8px; transition: all 0.2s; text-decoration: none; }
  .original-link:hover { border-color: var(--ember-border); color: var(--ember); }
  .original-link--gh { color: var(--ash); }

  .more-posts { padding: 4rem 0; border-top: 1px solid var(--border); }
  .more-posts-title { font-size: 0.72rem; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.1em; color: var(--text-lo); margin-bottom: 1.5rem; }
  .more-row { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 90px 1fr auto; gap: 1.5rem; align-items: baseline; padding: 1.25rem 0; border-top: 1px solid var(--border); cursor: pointer; transition: all 0.2s; text-decoration: none; }
  .more-row:hover { padding-left: 0.75rem; }
  .more-row:hover .more-title { color: var(--ember); }
  .more-date { font-size: 0.72rem; color: var(--text-lo); font-variant-numeric: tabular-nums; }
  .more-title { font-size: 0.85rem; color: var(--text-hi); transition: color 0.2s; }
  .more-src { font-size: 0.65rem; color: var(--text-lo); text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.06em; }

  @media (max-width: 768px) {
    .policy-row { grid-template-columns: 1fr; gap: 0.3rem; }
    .more-row { grid-template-columns: 1fr; gap: 0.3rem; }
    .post-hero { padding: 8rem 0 3rem; }
    .resource-links { flex-direction: column; }
  }
</style>
